<DemoExample Title="Basic" RazorCode="@example1RazorCode" CsharpCode="@example1CsharpCode" Id="example1" PreventRenderForMcpClient>
    <div>
        The ButtonGroup can be bound to a list of any class, without adapting that class to the component. The
        <strong>NameSelectors</strong> maps each of the component's fields onto the class, either by property name or by a
        selector expression, so an existing domain model can drive the group as it is.
    </div>
    <br />
    <BitButtonGroup Items="basicCustoms" NameSelectors="nameSelector" />
</DemoExample>

<DemoExample Title="Variant" RazorCode="@example2RazorCode" CsharpCode="@example2CsharpCode" Id="example2">
    <div>
        The visual style of the group is set by the <strong>Variant</strong>: Fill (default), Outline, or Text.
        The group can be disabled as a whole through <strong>IsEnabled</strong>, or one button at a time through the
        field mapped by the <strong>IsEnabled</strong> selector.
    </div>
    <br /><br />
    <div class="example-content">
        <div>Fill (default)</div>
        <BitButtonGroup Variant="BitVariant.Fill" Items="basicCustoms" NameSelectors="nameSelector" />
        <BitButtonGroup Variant="BitVariant.Fill" Items="disabledCustoms" NameSelectors="nameSelector" />
        <BitButtonGroup Variant="BitVariant.Fill" Items="basicCustoms" NameSelectors="nameSelector" IsEnabled="false" />
    </div>
    <br /><br />
    <div class="example-content">
        <div>Outline</div>
        <BitButtonGroup Variant="BitVariant.Outline" Items="basicCustoms" NameSelectors="nameSelector" />
        <BitButtonGroup Variant="BitVariant.Outline" Items="disabledCustoms" NameSelectors="nameSelector" />
        <BitButtonGroup Variant="BitVariant.Outline" Items="basicCustoms" NameSelectors="nameSelector" IsEnabled="false" />
    </div>
    <br /><br />
    <div class="example-content">
        <div>Text</div>
        <BitButtonGroup Variant="BitVariant.Text" Items="basicCustoms" NameSelectors="nameSelector" />
        <BitButtonGroup Variant="BitVariant.Text" Items="disabledCustoms" NameSelectors="nameSelector" />
        <BitButtonGroup Variant="BitVariant.Text" Items="basicCustoms" NameSelectors="nameSelector" IsEnabled="false" />
    </div>
</DemoExample>

<DemoExample Title="Icon" RazorCode="@example3RazorCode" CsharpCode="@example3CsharpCode" Id="example3" PreventRenderForMcpClient>
    <div>
        Each button can render an icon before its text by pointing the <strong>IconName</strong> selector at the field that
        holds the icon name — here the class calls it <strong>Image</strong>, which the selector maps for the component.
    </div>
    <br /><br />
    <div class="example-content">
        <div>Fill (default)</div>
        <BitButtonGroup Variant="BitVariant.Fill" Items="iconCustoms"
                        NameSelectors="@(new() { Text = { Selector = i => i.Name },
                                                 IconName = { Selector = i => i.Image } })" />
    </div>
    <br /><br />
    <div class="example-content">
        <div>Outline</div>
        <BitButtonGroup Variant="BitVariant.Outline" Items="iconCustoms"
                        NameSelectors="@(new() { Text = { Selector = i => i.Name },
                                                 IconName = { Selector = i => i.Image } })" />
    </div>
    <br /><br />
    <div class="example-content">
        <div>Text</div>
        <BitButtonGroup Variant="BitVariant.Text" Items="iconCustoms"
                        NameSelectors="@(new() { Text = { Selector = i => i.Name },
                                                 IconName = { Selector = i => i.Image } })" />
    </div>
</DemoExample>

<DemoExample Title="IconOnly" RazorCode="@example4RazorCode" CsharpCode="@example4CsharpCode" Id="example4" PreventRenderForMcpClient>
    <div>
        The <strong>IconOnly</strong> drops the text of every button and keeps only its icon, which suits compact toolbars
        and tight spaces. Because such a button has no visible label, map the <strong>AriaLabel</strong> selector (or at
        least <strong>Title</strong>) so it stays understandable to screen reader users.
    </div>
    <br /><br />
    <div class="example-content">
        <div>Fill (default)</div>
        <BitButtonGroup Variant="BitVariant.Fill" Items="iconCustoms"
                        NameSelectors="@(new() { Text = { Selector = i => i.Name },
                                                 IconName = { Selector = i => i.Image } })" IconOnly />
    </div>
    <br /><br />
    <div class="example-content">
        <div>Outline</div>
        <BitButtonGroup Variant="BitVariant.Outline" Items="iconCustoms"
                        NameSelectors="@(new() { Text = { Selector = i => i.Name },
                                                 IconName = { Selector = i => i.Image } })" IconOnly />
    </div>
    <br /><br />
    <div class="example-content">
        <div>Text</div>
        <BitButtonGroup Variant="BitVariant.Text" Items="iconCustoms"
                        NameSelectors="@(new() { Text = { Selector = i => i.Name },
                                                 IconName = { Selector = i => i.Image } })" IconOnly />
    </div>
    <br /><br />
    <div>Alternatively, each button can be set to IconOnly by simply leaving the text field empty.</div>
    <br /><br />
    <div class="example-content">
        <div>Fill (default)</div>
        <BitButtonGroup Variant="BitVariant.Fill" Items="onlyIconCustoms"
                        NameSelectors="@(new() { Text = { Selector = i => i.Name },
                                                 IconName = { Selector = i => i.Image } })" />
    </div>
    <br /><br />
    <div class="example-content">
        <div>Outline</div>
        <BitButtonGroup Variant="BitVariant.Outline" Items="onlyIconCustoms"
                        NameSelectors="@(new() { Text = { Selector = i => i.Name },
                                                 IconName = { Selector = i => i.Image } })" />
    </div>
    <br /><br />
    <div class="example-content">
        <div>Text</div>
        <BitButtonGroup Variant="BitVariant.Text" Items="onlyIconCustoms"
                        NameSelectors="@(new() { Text = { Selector = i => i.Name },
                                                 IconName = { Selector = i => i.Image } })" />
    </div>
</DemoExample>

<DemoExample Title="ReversedIcon" RazorCode="@example5RazorCode" CsharpCode="@example5CsharpCode" Id="example5" PreventRenderForMcpClient>
    <div>
        Mapping the <strong>ReversedIcon</strong> selector to a boolean field swaps the icon and the text of a button,
        putting the icon after the content instead of before it. It is read per item, so a single button can point the
        other way (useful for a trailing "next" arrow).
    </div>
    <br /><br />
    <div class="example-content">
        <div>Fill (default)</div>
        <BitButtonGroup Variant="BitVariant.Fill" Items="reversedIconCustoms"
                        NameSelectors="@(new() { Text = { Selector = i => i.Name },
                                                 IconName = { Selector = i => i.Image },
                                                 ReversedIcon = { Selector = i => i.ReversedIcon } })" />
    </div>
    <br /><br />
    <div class="example-content">
        <div>Outline</div>
        <BitButtonGroup Variant="BitVariant.Outline" Items="reversedIconCustoms"
                        NameSelectors="@(new() { Text = { Selector = i => i.Name },
                                                 IconName = { Selector = i => i.Image },
                                                 ReversedIcon = { Selector = i => i.ReversedIcon } })" />
    </div>
    <br /><br />
    <div class="example-content">
        <div>Text</div>
        <BitButtonGroup Variant="BitVariant.Text" Items="reversedIconCustoms"
                        NameSelectors="@(new() { Text = { Selector = i => i.Name },
                                                 IconName = { Selector = i => i.Image },
                                                 ReversedIcon = { Selector = i => i.ReversedIcon } })" />
    </div>
</DemoExample>

<DemoExample Title="Toggle" RazorCode="@example6RazorCode" CsharpCode="@example6CsharpCode" Id="example6" PreventRenderForMcpClient>
    <div>
        The <strong>Toggle</strong> turns the group into a single-select one, where at most one button is toggled at a time
        (a shorthand for <strong>SelectionMode="BitButtonGroupSelectionMode.Single"</strong>). It renders as a
        <strong>radiogroup</strong> whose buttons report their state through <strong>aria-checked</strong>. The component
        writes the toggle state back onto the class through the field named by the <strong>IsToggled</strong> selector, so
        the model always reflects what is toggled. The toggled key is read and set through <strong>ToggleKey</strong>,
        seeded by <strong>DefaultToggleKey</strong>, and every change raises <strong>OnToggleChange</strong>.
    </div>
    <br /><br />
    <div class="example-content">
        <div>Fill (default)</div>
        <BitButtonGroup Toggle Items="toggledCustoms" Variant="BitVariant.Fill" NameSelectors="toggledNameSelectors" />
    </div>
    <br /><br />
    <div class="example-content">
        <div>Outline</div>
        <BitButtonGroup Toggle Items="toggledCustoms" Variant="BitVariant.Outline" NameSelectors="toggledNameSelectors" />
    </div>
    <br /><br />
    <div class="example-content">
        <div>Text</div>
        <BitButtonGroup Toggle Items="toggledCustoms" Variant="BitVariant.Text" NameSelectors="toggledNameSelectors" />
    </div>
    <br /><br /><br /><br />
    <div>Binding:</div><br />
    <BitButtonGroup Toggle Variant="BitVariant.Outline" Items="toggledCustoms" NameSelectors="toggledNameSelectors" @bind-ToggleKey="toggleKey" />
    <div>Toggle key: @toggleKey</div>
    <BitButton OnClick="@(() => toggleKey = "forward")">Forward</BitButton>
    <br /><br /><br /><br />
    <div>OnToggleChange:</div><br />
    <BitButtonGroup Toggle Variant="BitVariant.Outline" Items="changeToggledCustoms" NameSelectors="toggledNameSelectors" DefaultToggleKey="forward" OnToggleChange="(Operation o) => onChangeToggleCustom = o" />
    <div>Changed toggle: @onChangeToggleCustom?.Id , @onChangeToggleCustom?.IsSelected</div>
    <br /><br /><br /><br />
    <div>
        <strong>FixedToggle</strong> makes the selection mandatory: clicking the toggled button no longer un-toggles it,
        so the group always keeps exactly one answer.
    </div><br />
    <BitButtonGroup Toggle FixedToggle Variant="BitVariant.Outline" Items="fixedSingleCustoms" NameSelectors="multiNameSelectors" DefaultToggleKey="medium" />
</DemoExample>

<DemoExample Title="Vertical" RazorCode="@example7RazorCode" CsharpCode="@example7CsharpCode" Id="example7" PreventRenderForMcpClient>
    <div>
        By default the ButtonGroup lays its buttons out horizontally; the <strong>Vertical</strong> stacks them instead,
        moving the separators between the buttons from their sides to their edges. The keyboard navigation follows the
        layout, so the Up and Down arrow keys take over from Left and Right.
    </div>
    <br /><br />
    <div class="buttons-container">
        <div class="example-content">
            <div>Fill (default)</div>
            <BitButtonGroup Variant="BitVariant.Fill" Items="basicCustoms" NameSelectors="nameSelector" Vertical />
        </div>
        <br /><br />
        <div class="example-content">
            <div>Outline</div>
            <BitButtonGroup Variant="BitVariant.Outline" Items="basicCustoms" NameSelectors="nameSelector" Vertical />
        </div>
        <br /><br />
        <div class="example-content">
            <div>Text</div>
            <BitButtonGroup Variant="BitVariant.Text" Items="basicCustoms" NameSelectors="nameSelector" Vertical />
        </div>
    </div>
</DemoExample>

<DemoExample Title="Events" RazorCode="@example8RazorCode" CsharpCode="@example8CsharpCode" Id="example8" PreventRenderForMcpClient>
    <div>
        Clicks can be handled in two places: the group's <strong>OnItemClick</strong> receives whichever item was clicked,
        and the <strong>OnClick</strong> selector points at a field on the class holding a per-item delegate. Both run on
        every click, the group's callback first. Disabled and loading buttons raise neither.
    </div>
    <br /><br />
    <div class="example-content">
        <div>Component's ItemClick event:</div>
        <BitButtonGroup Items="basicCustoms"
                        NameSelectors="nameSelector"
                        OnItemClick="(Operation item) => clickedCustom = item.Name" />
        <div>Clicked item: <b>@clickedCustom</b></div>
    </div>
    <br /><br />
    <div class="example-content">
        <div>Item's Click event:</div>
        <BitButtonGroup Items="eventsCustoms"
                        NameSelectors="@(new() { Text = { Selector = i => i.Name },
                                                 IconName = { Selector = i => i.Image },
                                                 OnClick = { Selector = i => i.Clicked } })" />
        <div>Click count: <b>@clickCounter</b></div>
    </div>
</DemoExample>

<DemoExample Title="FullWidth" RazorCode="@example9RazorCode" CsharpCode="@example9CsharpCode" Id="example9" PreventRenderForMcpClient>
    <div>
        The <strong>FullWidth</strong> stretches the group to 100% of its container's width. The extra space is shared by
        the buttons in proportion to their content, so wider labels stay wider — pair it with
        <BitLink Href="#example11"><strong>Justified</strong></BitLink> when every button should end up the same width.
    </div>
    <br /><br />
    <div class="example-content">
        <BitButtonGroup FullWidth Variant="BitVariant.Fill" Items="basicCustoms" NameSelectors="nameSelector" />
        <BitButtonGroup FullWidth Variant="BitVariant.Outline" Items="basicCustoms" NameSelectors="nameSelector" />
        <BitButtonGroup FullWidth Variant="BitVariant.Text" Items="basicCustoms" NameSelectors="nameSelector" />
    </div>
</DemoExample>

<DemoExample Title="Multiple" RazorCode="@example10RazorCode" CsharpCode="@example10CsharpCode" Id="example10" PreventRenderForMcpClient>
    <div>
        Setting the <strong>SelectionMode</strong> to <strong>Multiple</strong> lets any number of buttons be toggled at the
        same time. The toggled keys are available through the <strong>ToggleKeys</strong> two-way bound parameter.
    </div>
    <br /><br />
    <div class="example-content">
        <div>Binding:</div>
        <BitButtonGroup Variant="BitVariant.Outline"
                        SelectionMode="BitButtonGroupSelectionMode.Multiple"
                        Items="formatCustoms"
                        NameSelectors="multiNameSelectors"
                        @bind-ToggleKeys="formatKeys" />
        <div>Toggle keys: <b>@string.Join(", ", formatKeys ?? [])</b></div>
    </div>
    <br /><br />
    <div class="example-content">
        <div><strong>MaxToggles</strong> caps how many buttons can be toggled at once:</div>
        <BitButtonGroup Variant="BitVariant.Outline"
                        SelectionMode="BitButtonGroupSelectionMode.Multiple"
                        MaxToggles="2"
                        Items="maxToggleCustoms"
                        NameSelectors="multiNameSelectors"
                        DefaultToggleKeys="@defaultKeys" />
    </div>
    <br /><br />
    <div class="example-content">
        <div><strong>FixedToggle</strong> keeps at least one button toggled:</div>
        <BitButtonGroup Variant="BitVariant.Outline"
                        SelectionMode="BitButtonGroupSelectionMode.Multiple"
                        FixedToggle
                        Items="fixedToggleCustoms"
                        NameSelectors="multiNameSelectors"
                        DefaultToggleKeys="@defaultKeys" />
    </div>
</DemoExample>

<DemoExample Title="Justified" RazorCode="@example11RazorCode" CsharpCode="@example11CsharpCode" Id="example11" PreventRenderForMcpClient>
    <div>
        The Justified gives every button an equal width, so the buttons evenly fill the ButtonGroup.
        Combined with FullWidth it turns the ButtonGroup into a segmented control.
    </div>
    <br /><br />
    <div class="example-content">
        <div>Default (buttons are sized by their content)</div>
        <BitButtonGroup FullWidth Variant="BitVariant.Outline" Items="justifiedCustoms" NameSelectors="nameSelector" />
        <br />
        <div>Justified (buttons share the width equally)</div>
        <BitButtonGroup FullWidth Justified Variant="BitVariant.Outline" Items="justifiedCustoms" NameSelectors="nameSelector" />
    </div>
</DemoExample>

<DemoExample Title="Detached" RazorCode="@example12RazorCode" CsharpCode="@example12CsharpCode" Id="example12" PreventRenderForMcpClient>
    <div>
        The <strong>Detached</strong> breaks the buttons apart: the border and the rounding move from the group onto each
        button, so they read as separate buttons that still share the group's color, size, and selection behavior.
        The <strong>Gap</strong> takes any CSS length and sets the space between them.
    </div>
    <br /><br />
    <div class="example-content">
        <div>Fill (default)</div>
        <BitButtonGroup Detached Variant="BitVariant.Fill" Items="basicCustoms" NameSelectors="nameSelector" />
    </div>
    <br /><br />
    <div class="example-content">
        <div>Outline</div>
        <BitButtonGroup Detached Variant="BitVariant.Outline" Items="basicCustoms" NameSelectors="nameSelector" />
    </div>
    <br /><br />
    <div class="example-content">
        <div>Gap</div>
        <BitButtonGroup Detached Gap="1.5rem" Variant="BitVariant.Outline" Items="basicCustoms" NameSelectors="nameSelector" />
    </div>
</DemoExample>

<DemoExample Title="Rounded" RazorCode="@example13RazorCode" CsharpCode="@example13CsharpCode" Id="example13" PreventRenderForMcpClient>
    <div>
        The <strong>Rounded</strong> renders pill shaped corners. On an attached group only the outer corners are rounded,
        while combining it with <strong>Detached</strong> turns every button into its own pill.
    </div>
    <br /><br />
    <div class="example-content">
        <div>Attached</div>
        <BitButtonGroup Rounded Variant="BitVariant.Fill" Items="basicCustoms" NameSelectors="nameSelector" />
        <BitButtonGroup Rounded Variant="BitVariant.Outline" Items="basicCustoms" NameSelectors="nameSelector" />
    </div>
    <br /><br />
    <div class="example-content">
        <div>Detached</div>
        <BitButtonGroup Rounded Detached Variant="BitVariant.Fill" Items="basicCustoms" NameSelectors="nameSelector" />
        <BitButtonGroup Rounded Detached Variant="BitVariant.Outline" Items="basicCustoms" NameSelectors="nameSelector" />
    </div>
</DemoExample>

<DemoExample Title="Overflow" RazorCode="@example14RazorCode" CsharpCode="@example14CsharpCode" Id="example14" PreventRenderForMcpClient>
    <div>
        The <strong>Overflow</strong> decides what happens when the buttons do not fit: <strong>Wrap</strong> moves them onto
        more lines, <strong>Scroll</strong> keeps one line and lets the group scroll sideways &mdash; by swiping, by
        shift+wheel, or with the arrow keys, since the scrollbar itself is hidden so that the border keeps hugging
        the buttons &mdash; <strong>Scrollbar</strong> does the same but keeps the scrollbar visible as an affordance,
        at the cost of the height it occupies inside the border, and <strong>Clip</strong> (the default) keeps one line
        and cuts the rest off. Drag the bottom-right corner of the dashed boxes below to resize
        them and watch the behavior change.
    </div>
    <br /><br />
    <div class="example-content">
        <div>Wrap</div>
        <div class="overflow-container">
            <BitButtonGroup FullWidth
                            Variant="BitVariant.Outline"
                            Overflow="BitButtonGroupOverflow.Wrap"
                            Items="overflowCustoms"
                            NameSelectors="nameSelector" />
        </div>
    </div>
    <br /><br />
    <div class="example-content">
        <div>Scroll</div>
        <div class="overflow-container">
            <BitButtonGroup FullWidth
                            Variant="BitVariant.Outline"
                            Overflow="BitButtonGroupOverflow.Scroll"
                            Items="overflowCustoms"
                            NameSelectors="nameSelector" />
        </div>
    </div>
    <br /><br />
    <div class="example-content">
        <div>Scrollbar</div>
        <div class="overflow-container">
            <BitButtonGroup FullWidth
                            Variant="BitVariant.Outline"
                            Overflow="BitButtonGroupOverflow.Scrollbar"
                            Items="overflowCustoms"
                            NameSelectors="nameSelector" />
        </div>
    </div>
</DemoExample>

