<DemoExample Title="Templates" RazorCode="@example18RazorCode" CsharpCode="@example18CsharpCode" Id="example18" PreventRenderForMcpClient>
    <div>
        The content of the buttons can be replaced entirely: the group's <strong>ItemTemplate</strong> re-renders every
        button, while the <strong>Template</strong> selector points at a field holding a per-item template that re-renders
        only that one and wins over the group's template. A template replaces the icon, text, and badge, so anything the
        button needs has to be part of it.
    </div>
    <br /><br />
    <div class="example-content">
        <div>ItemTemplate (applies to every button):</div>
        <BitButtonGroup Variant="BitVariant.Outline" Items="templateCustoms" NameSelectors="nameSelector">
            <ItemTemplate Context="item">
                <div class="custom-template">
                    <BitIcon IconName="@item.Image" />
                    <span>@item.Name</span>
                </div>
            </ItemTemplate>
        </BitButtonGroup>
    </div>
    <br /><br />
    <div class="example-content">
        <div>Template selector (applies to a single button):</div>
        <BitButtonGroup Variant="BitVariant.Outline" Items="itemTemplateCustoms" NameSelectors="templateNameSelectors" />
    </div>
</DemoExample>

<DemoExample Title="Tooltips" RazorCode="@example19RazorCode" CsharpCode="@example19CsharpCode" Id="example19" PreventRenderForMcpClient>
    <div>
        Mapping the <strong>Title</strong> selector gives a button a native tooltip, which is the cheapest way to explain an
        icon-only button on hover. In a toggle group, the <strong>OnTitle</strong> and <strong>OffTitle</strong> selectors
        let the tooltip follow the toggle state and fall back to Title when they are not mapped. A tooltip is not an
        accessible name, so keep mapping <strong>AriaLabel</strong> for icon-only buttons.
    </div>
    <br /><br />
    <div class="example-content">
        <div>Hover the buttons to see their tooltips:</div>
        <BitButtonGroup IconOnly Variant="BitVariant.Outline" Items="titleCustoms" NameSelectors="titleNameSelectors" />
    </div>
    <br /><br />
    <div class="example-content">
        <div>OnTitle &amp; OffTitle (toggle the button and hover it again):</div>
        <BitButtonGroup Toggle
                        Variant="BitVariant.Outline"
                        Items="toggleTitleCustoms"
                        NameSelectors="toggleTitleNameSelectors"
                        DefaultToggleKey="mute" />
    </div>
</DemoExample>

<DemoExample Title="Accessibility" RazorCode="@example20RazorCode" CsharpCode="@example20CsharpCode" Id="example20" PreventRenderForMcpClient>
    <div>
        The ButtonGroup follows the WAI-ARIA patterns: it renders as a <strong>radiogroup</strong> of radio buttons in the
        Single selection mode and as a <strong>toolbar</strong> of toggle buttons otherwise, and the whole group is a single
        tab stop that the arrow, Home, and End keys navigate (a roving tabindex). Always give the group an AriaLabel.
    </div>
    <br /><br />
    <div class="example-content">
        <div>Tab into the group, then navigate it using the arrow, Home, and End keys:</div>
        <BitButtonGroup AriaLabel="Text alignment"
                        Variant="BitVariant.Outline"
                        SelectionMode="BitButtonGroupSelectionMode.Single"
                        Items="a11yCustoms"
                        NameSelectors="a11yNameSelectors"
                        DefaultToggleKey="start" />
    </div>
    <br /><br />
    <div class="example-content">
        <div><strong>SelectOnFocus</strong> makes the selection follow the keyboard focus:</div>
        <BitButtonGroup AriaLabel="Text alignment (selection follows focus)"
                        SelectOnFocus
                        Variant="BitVariant.Outline"
                        SelectionMode="BitButtonGroupSelectionMode.Single"
                        Items="selectOnFocusCustoms"
                        NameSelectors="a11yNameSelectors"
                        DefaultToggleKey="start" />
    </div>
    <br /><br />
    <div class="example-content">
        <div><strong>DisabledInteractive</strong> keeps the disabled buttons focusable, so they stay discoverable:</div>
        <BitButtonGroup AriaLabel="Operations with a disabled button"
                        DisabledInteractive
                        Variant="BitVariant.Outline"
                        Items="disabledCustoms"
                        NameSelectors="nameSelector" />
